<Base title="Australia–India Bilateral" description="Nikhil Kulkarni's work at the Australia–India intersection: AIBC, AIYD, New India House at SXSW Sydney, and the Track 1.5 Strategic Dialogue.">

  <div class="page-header">
    <p class="page-label">Community &amp; Ecosystem</p>
    <h1>Australia–India Bilateral</h1>
    <p class="intro">The Australia–India relationship is one of the most consequential bilateral partnerships of our time. I've spent years working at this intersection: in business, technology, policy, and culture.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="content">

    <section class="role-section">
      <div class="role-tag">Active</div>
      <h2>Ambassador, India Australia Business &amp; Community Alliance (IABCA)</h2>
      <p>The <strong>India Australia Business &amp; Community Alliance (IABCA)</strong> brings together a distinguished network of leaders shaping the Australia–India corridor — across technology, entrepreneurship, government, and community. I was welcomed into the <strong>IABCA Ambassador Circle</strong> in June 2026, in recognition of work spanning product leadership, AI, and Australia–India community engagement.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="role-section">
      <div class="role-tag">Active</div>
      <h2>NSW Management Committee, Australia India Business Council</h2>
      <p>The <strong>Australia India Business Council (AIBC)</strong> is a leading organisation strengthening business, trade, and investment ties between Australia and India. I serve on the NSW Management Committee, contributing to strategy, programs, and community engagement that deepen the Australia–India corridor.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="role-section">
      <div class="role-tag">2025</div>
      <h2>Program Director, New India House at SXSW Sydney</h2>
      <p><strong>New India House</strong> was a flagship India-focused platform at SXSW Sydney 2025, the Asia-Pacific edition of the iconic Austin festival. A fusion of innovation, tech, and culture bringing together leaders across technology, entrepreneurship, government, and policy.</p>
      <p>As <strong>Program Director</strong>, I led the vision and program design from scratch: program management, content, branding, marketing, and cross-sector coordination, all pulled together in a matter of weeks. One of the programs I moderated was "Namast-AI to the Future! Why India Is Essential to Your AI Success", a panel at the intersection of the two things I care most about.</p>
      <p>The whole thing began with a chance meeting at AIYD 2024. A real example of how community relationships compound.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="role-section">
      <div class="role-tag">2024</div>
      <h2>Delegate, Australia India Youth Dialogue</h2>
      <p>Selected as a delegate for the <strong>Australia India Youth Dialogue (AIYD) 2024</strong>, a high-profile bilateral dialogue bringing together emerging leaders from Australia and India across technology, entrepreneurship, and cross-border collaboration. The connections made at AIYD directly led to the New India House role at SXSW.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="role-section">
      <div class="role-tag">2026</div>
      <h2>Australia–India Track 1.5 Strategic Dialogue</h2>
      <p>In May 2026, I was invited to speak at the <strong>Australia–India Strategic and Technology Track 1.5 Dialogue</strong> on Digital Public Infrastructure and AI, co-organised by the Asia Society Australia and the Ananta Aspen Centre. I presented three concrete use cases for deeper cooperation between Australia and India on digital infrastructure and AI governance.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="role-section">
      <h2>Writing on Australia–India</h2>
      <p>I write regularly on the Australia–India relationship, covering migration, technology, trade, and culture. Published pieces include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="https://www.smh.com.au/national/india-is-now-australia-s-no-1-source-of-migrants-it-s-a-profound-shift-and-a-positive-one-20260601-p602qt.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>India is now Australia's No.1 source of migrants</em></a>, Sydney Morning Herald, June 2026</li>
        <li><em>ECTA four years on — what's worked, what hasn't</em>, draft commentary on the Australia–India free trade agreement</li>
      </ul>
      <p><a href="/writing">See all writing →</a></p>
    </section>

  </div>

